Thought my chunking strategy really helped my endurance and focus this race:
Miles 1-2: Warmup
Miles 3-13: Run Loose
Miles 14-21: Run Strong (focus on cadence)
Miles 22-26: Let It Rip

Activity Name: Might still be able to run this race 🙏🏼
Activity Description:
Ran by easy effort and expected to be way slower but it felt so good to be out there again and I was very tapered lol. Original diagnosis was a stress fracture but today the PT pumped my posterior tibialis tendon with numbing medicine and told me to go for a run (which naturally meant I cancelled my afternoon meetings with hesitation). 

And I had zero pain which most likely rules out a stress fracture! We will see how my next run goes without being drugged up but feeling hopeful.

Man that race chewed me up and spit me out 😂. But bucket list goal achieved and what an electric experience! So many runners and spectators. There was nonstop cheering and some stretches were so loud it sounded like the finishing chute. My favorite moment was Wellesley College where I was given a hundred high fives. Also seeing Paige all but leaping over the rail to get my attention in the final stretch which gave me a much needed energy boost.

My singular goal for this training block was to get to the start line fully healthy and we made it 🙏. Having to drop out of Boston last year was tough and it took longer than expected to trust my body to run without fearing another stress fracture or having tendonitis flare ups. Was able to work through it by keeping the recovery runs very easy and ramping the mileage slowly and I really enjoyed having a training goal this block of “feeling good”. 

Kept telling myself and everyone that I didn’t have a time goal today because I wanted to just enjoy this as a celebration run. But in a cruel irony, this was the hardest race I’ve ever done—as if the marathon gods were laughing at me for saying my goal was to “enjoy it”. 😅 Blacked out after crossing the finish line but the support staff caught me and carted me to the medical tent to help me recover. Not totally sure why things went so south but I really started to hurt pretty early on. I think it’s because it was super sunny and I went out too fast and my heart rate spiked too early. Played a lot of mind games to force myself to keep moving but didn’t come this far to DNF!

Marathons are always hard and I have a newfound respect for anyone who conquers the distance regardless of pace. Highlight of the trip was the conversations I had with runners from all over the world. I’m grateful for this community of crazy, supportive, wonderful people. “If you are losing faith in human nature, go out and watch a marathon.” 💙💛

Got an MRI after minimal symptom improvement the past few weeks and turns out what I thought was a muscle strain was actually a femoral neck stress reaction so gotta shut it down for the season. 

After a relatively conservative Boston build focused on just finishing healthy, the goal for this build was to shoot for peak fitness with a higher risk tolerance. But now I know that in the 2 out of 8 marathon training cycles where I’ve gotten injured, a common denominator is that I increased frequency to six days of running per week. The frustrating part is that both of those cycles I felt like I was reaching new fitness levels and feeling strong, but apparently my bones didn’t sign the participation waiver. So I probably need to stick to more recovery days or build to six days more slowly and not increase intensity and mileage at the same time. And also dial in nutrition. But it’s experience that should help me train smarter in the future.

A lot of the joy I find in running is pushing myself to test my limits and I had a ton of fun this summer training and nailing some challenging workouts even if I don’t have a PR race to show for it. So no regrets and a good time to diversify my hobbies while I wait for my bone to heal up.
